<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-685-677  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 685 677.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 26 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hitachi-developed CD-ROM application system.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazawa, Naoyuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hitachi Ltd. (Product development).andO;Topic:     Product DevelopmentCD-ROM XAMultimedia technology.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HITACHI-DEVELOPED CD-ROM APPLICATION SYSTEM 11/26/90 TOKYO, JAPAN, 1990 NOV26 (NB) -- Hitachi has developed a portable multimedia system based on theCD-ROM/XA format.andP;  It comes with a 5-inch color LCD (liquid crystal display)and a 12 centimeter CD-ROM (compact disk-read only memory) drive, on a trialbasis.andP;  The prototype machine is an interactive multimedia tool and all thefunctions, such as color display, image processing and control units, arepacked in an A4 file size and 70 millimeter-high body as a stand-alonesystem.andM;The color display unit will process an image with 640 by 480 standardpersonal computer graphic resolution, and pick up 256 colors from the paletteof 256,000 colors.andP;  Consequently 2,000 still pictures can be stored on a12-centimeter CD-ROM disk.andM;The audio signal processing unit will retrieve data on a CD-ROM and output toa built-in speaker, outer audio or headphone terminal as a stereo signal.andM;Also, its control unit employs a 16-bit CPU (central processing unit) and hasan MS-DOS emulation function.andM;Since the portable machine based on the CD-ROM/XA format is the first in theworld, it establishes Hitachi's technical advantage in this arena for theimmediate future.andM;(Naoyuki Yazawa/19901121/Press Contact: Hitachi Co., Ltd. 045-881-4970)</TEXT></DOC>